US rates twist- steepen as Fed lersip remains in focus; US PCE and consumer sentiment in line with expectations; gold rallies as equities sell off; Canada GDP underperforms; UK fiscal concerns; Axj weakens on domestic policy events; DXY at 97.771(+0.0%); US 10y at 4.232% (+2.5bp).
US rates twist- steepen as risk sentiment softens while uncertainty around Fed leadership and US trade policy remains high.

- Front-end US rates rally (2y: -1bp) modestly with light signals from new economic data. 2y yields open slightly higher and show little reaction to the US PCE print. Core and headline inflation largely align with expectations (Core: 0.27% m/m; Headline: 0.20%), though our economists note stronger price acceleration in tariff-exposed goods (for more, see here). Front-end rates trend lower as consumer sentiment comes in slightly soft (58.2; C: 58.6) and 5-10y inflation expectations drop to 3.5% from 3.9%, potentially hinting at more room for a September Fed cut.

- Long-end rates sell off (30y: +5bp) amid continued developments at the Fed, in a reversal of Thursday's flattening. Uncertainty remains high as the emergency court hearing on Governor Cook's removal concludes with no ruling expected until at least Tuesday, though Governor Cook currently maintains her role at the Fed.

- After markets close, the US administration's country-specific tariffs face legal challenges. The US Court of Appeals finds that the emergency authorities invoked by President Trump do not allow for tariffs, but all current tariffs can remain in place as the case likely proceeds to the US Supreme Court. Our public policy strategists note that the administration has numerous alternate pathways to maintain or reimpose tariffs.

- US equities sell off and gold rallies 0.9% as risk sentiment retreats. Al optimism wanes as market participants perceive mixed results from large-cap tech earnings, resulting in a tech-led sell-off which sees the S&P Equal Weight Index (-0.05%) outperform the S&P 500 (-0.6%). Cyclical sectors underperform, including Industrials (S&P Industrials: -1.0%) and Consumer discretionary (-1.1%).

- USD trades sideways (DXY: +0.0%), with GBP underperforming (GBP/ USD: -0.1%) among G10 currencies. UK gilts sell off in a bear-steepening fashion (2y: +1bp; 30y: +3bp) after third-party proposals for a tax on local banks draw attention to fiscal sustainability concerns. In Canada, 2Q GDP underperforms expectations (-1.6%; C: -0.7%) driven by weaker exports. Canadian rates bull-steepen (2y: -5bp; 30y: -3bp) as markets price higher likelihood of a BoC cut in September. - European rates bear-steepen (2y Bund: +1bp; 30y:+4bp) in sympathy with the US and UK. The sell-off is supported by a slight downside surprise in German CPI (2.2% y/y; C: 2.1%). Spreads between bunds and other European government bonds continue to widen, with Italian BTPs (10y: +3bp) underperforming French OATs (10y: +2bp).

- Super-long JGBs continue to strengthen in anticipation of potential reductions in issuance, seemingly supported by demand from end-of-month portfolio duration extensions. 2y JGBs initial trade somewhat higher following Thursday's weak auction, showing little reaction to the August Tokyo CPI print, which falls largely in line with expectations (2.6% y/y; C: 2.6%). The JGB curve ultimately bull-flattens (5y: -1bp; 30y: -4bp). The TONA swap curve bull-flattens as well, but underperforms JGBs in long-end sectors. A 10y auction is scheduled on Tuesday.

- In CEEMEA, Czech rates sell off and CZK rallies on an upside surprise in 2Q GDP(2.6% y/y; C: 2.4%). Accordingly, yields rise in the Czech Republic by \(\sim\)5bp across the curve. CZK strengthens 0.3% against EUR and 0.4% against USD. Rates also sell off in Hungary, where the curve bear-steepens (2y: +1bp; 10y: +6bp).
Axi currencies and rates broadly weaken on political developments, with central banks reportedly considering action.

- In Indonesia, IDR weakens 0.9% against USD to a three-month low and rates bear-steepen (2y IndoGB: +3bp; 10y: +4bp) amid domestic political uncertainties, with BI officials stating the central bank is prepared to stabilize IDR, potentially by intervening in FX, bond, domestic, and offshore markets.- In India, INR weakens 0.7% to a historic low of 88.2 per USD following Wednesday's US tariff implementation, despite showing limited initial reaction on Thursday. Unconfirmed reports suggest potential FX intervention by the RBI. Following an upside surprise in 2Q GDP (7.8% y/y; C: 6.7%), Indian rates sell off in a bear-steepening (10y IGB: +6bp), which is reflected in weak demand at the 15y and 40y IGB auctions.- In Thailand, local equities sell off (SET 50: -1.2%) and USD/THB rises 0.1% after the Constitutional Court dismisses Prime Minister Paetongtarn, setting up an auction for a new prime minister. Meanwhile, Thailand's July exports slow to 9.7% y/y from 16.1% in June.

- San Francisco Fed President Daly stated "it will soon be time to recalibrate policy to better match our economy," emphasizing that tariff-related price increases "will be a one off."

- In Mexico, Banxico increased its 2025 GDP forecast to \(0.6\%\) from \(0.1\%\) . Deputy Governor Heath stated that the economy was unlikely to enter a recession, but despite the GDP revision, much more growth was needed.  
- In Indonesia, BI Executive Director Erwin reiterated the central bank's intent to closely monitor market movements and respond accordingly to ensure IDR moves in line with its fundamentals. He said BI will remain present in the market and to intervene across FX spot, bonds, and onshore/offshore NDF markets to stabilize the currency. He added BI will continue to optimize policies to ensure interest rate policy transmission and increase liquidity.

- In the Philippines, BSP Governor Remolona reiterated that the Philippines has reached a "sweet spot" for both inflation and growth. He said "if the numbers stay the way they are, then we won't need another rate cut," but there are signs of weakness (e.g., PMI) and if the weakness materializes, then there is room for one more rate cut. He added that the BSP is mainly concerned about the risk of Philippines' exports declining. Remolona indicated the central bank is looking at a real interest rate of 2%, with a nominal rate of 4% being "a bit low".

- US July Real Personal Spending: \(0.3\%\) m/m (MSe: \(0.3\%\) ; C: \(0.3\%\) ; P: \(0.1\%\) ). We expect real spending growth to slow, with the peak of the weakness in Q4 of this year and Q1 of next year. Real goods spending was strong, up \(0.9\%\) . Real services spending rose \(0.1\%\) , a similar pace to the past few months. Spending was revised slightly higher in May and June. Real durable goods spending rose \(2.0\%\) in July, boosted by a \(4.5\%\) m/m increase in autos. Autos contributed 0.16pp to the 0.3pp rise in real spending. This month's rise could be payback, or it also could be some demand pulled forward before the EV credits expire next month. Real spending on nondurable goods rose \(0.3\%\) , with strength in groceries and clothing. The \(0.1\%\) m/m increase in real services spending is in line with recent trends, a slowdown from last year's pace.

- US July Personal Income: \(0.4\%\) m/m (MSe: \(0.4\%\) m/m; C: \(0.4\%\) ; P: \(0.3\%\) ). Nominal labor compensation was stronger, up \(0.6\%\) . The saving rate remained constant m/m at \(4.4\%\) . On net, spending remains solid, supported by income growth that is still outpacing inflation.

- US July Core PCE Prices: \(0.27\%\) m/m (MSe: \(0.27\%\) m/m; C: \(0.3\%\) ; P: \(0.3\%\) ) & Headline PCE Price: \(0.20\%\) m/m (MSe: \(0.22\%\) ; C: \(0.2\%\) ; P: \(0.3\%\) ). Overall minor changes. As expected, June was revised higher (+0.6bp), but there were downward revisions to April and May (-1bp each). The 12-month pace increased to \(2.88\%\) y/y (vs. \(2.77\%\) in June). Core PCE annualized inflation in the last 3 months came in at \(2.98\%\) (2.55% in June), with the 6-month annualized pace at \(2.99\%\) (3.14% in June). Core goods moved sideways in June, but the details still show a clear tariff-induced acceleration. Core services accelerated despite softer healthcare inflation. Despite the acceleration in prices, we think the Fed will start cutting rates in the September FOMC meeting to reduce the risks of a meaningful deterioration in labor markets ahead.

- US July Trade Balance: -90.2bn (MSe: -98.0bn; C: -90.0bn; P: -86.0bn). We are tracking 3Q GDP at a 1.4% annual rate, up a tenth from prior estimates. Equipment investment bumps up to 8% on solid imports of capital goods. High uncertainty around the trade data, as gold flows look large but will not be detailed in the report until next week.

- US August UMich Consumer Sentiment: 58.2 (C: 58.6; P: 58.6) & 5-10 Year Inflation Expectation: 3.5% (C: 3.9%; P: 3.9%). Inflation expectations are little changed from July's 3.4%, but down from the 4.2% average in 2Q. Other

elements of the survey remain very weak, but these have de- linked from spending over the past several years, seemingly much more sensitive to actual and expected inflation than to other drivers of real spending (e.g., jobs, incomes, wealth).

When the 5- day moving average crosses above the 20- day moving average, buy the futures contract (long duration) and hold for a 25- business- day period. When the 5- day moving average crosses below the 20- day moving average, buy the futures contract and hold for a 25- business- day period. In short, this strategy buys futures when the Simple Moving Average Crossover (SMAX) generates both a long and a short signal, given the historical outperformance of long signals traded long and the underperformance of short signals traded short. Given that the SMAX could generate both a long and a short signal within the predefined holding period, an investor may have a 200% long position since each of the two signals would be traded in separate portfolio sleeves.
